Some "typical" logical errors (i.e., these are wrong):

  • Assuming that p\implies q \equiv q\implies pp  ⟹  q≡q  ⟹  pp\implies q \equiv q\implies pp⟹q≡q⟹p
  • Assuming that p\implies q \equiv \neg p\implies \neg qp  ⟹  q≡¬p  ⟹  ¬qp\implies q \equiv \neg p\implies \neg qp⟹q≡¬p⟹¬q

What is true however is that p\implies qp  ⟹  qp\implies qp⟹q is equivalent to \neg q \implies \neg p¬q  ⟹  ¬p\neg q \implies \neg p¬q⟹¬p. Tthis is called the contrapositive statement and you should probably remember this one (together with De Morgan's laws).

a) The argument is invalid. Say n=-2n=−2n=-2n=−2, then n^2 = 4 > 1n2=4>1n^2 = 4 > 1n2=4>1 but n\leq 1n≤1n\leq 1n≤1. The argument used n^2>1\implies n>1n2>1  ⟹  n>1n^2>1\implies n>1n2>1⟹n>1 which is not equivalent to the actual true proposition n>1\implies n^2>1n>1  ⟹  n2>1n>1\implies n^2>1n>1⟹n2>1. In general, p\implies qp  ⟹  qp\implies qp⟹q is not equivalent to q\implies pq  ⟹  pq\implies pq⟹p.

b) The statement n>3\implies n^2>3n>3  ⟹  n2>3n>3\implies n^2>3n>3⟹n2>3 is true and its contrapositive statement is n^2\leq3\implies n\leq3n2≤3  ⟹  n≤3n^2\leq3\implies n\leq3n2≤3⟹n≤3. The contrapositive statement is logically equivalent to the original statement so the argument is valid.

c) Here it is assumed that n>2\implies n^2>4n>2  ⟹  n2>4n>2\implies n^2>4n>2⟹n2>4 is equivalent to n\leq2\implies n^2\leq4n≤2  ⟹  n2≤4n\leq2\implies n^2\leq4n≤2⟹n2≤4. But in genereal, p\implies qp  ⟹  qp\implies qp⟹q is not equivalent to \neg p\implies \neg q¬p  ⟹  ¬q\neg p\implies \neg q¬p⟹¬q. For example, take n=-3\leq 2n=−3≤2n=-3\leq 2n=−3≤2, then n^2=9>4n2=9>4n^2=9>4n2=9>4.

Remember that \textbf{F}\implies pF  ⟹  p\textbf{F}\implies pF⟹p is always a true statement regardless of the truth value of pppp. A proof using this fact is called vacuous proof.

For example, let P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) : "if xxxx is a prime number, then x=2x=2x=2x=2 or xxxx is an odd number."

Now, let us prove P(4) : "if 4444 is a prime number \implies  ⟹  \implies⟹ ..." but this is always true since 4444 is not a prime so the left-hand side is false meaning that we have a statement on the form \textbf{F}\implies pF  ⟹  p\textbf{F}\implies pF⟹p.

P(n)P(n)P(n)P(n) : "If nnnn is a positive integer greater than 1111, then n^2 > nn2>nn^2 > nn2>n."

The proposition P(0)P(0)P(0)P(0) reads as follows: "If 0000 is a positive integer greater than 1111, then 0^2 > 002>00^2 > 002>0". Written symbolically: (0\in\mathbb{Z} \wedge 0>1)\implies 0^2 > 0(0∈Z∧0>1)  ⟹  02>0(0\in\mathbb{Z} \wedge 0>1)\implies 0^2 > 0(0∈Z∧0>1)⟹02>0. But the premise 0>10>10>10>1 is false, so the proposition P(0)P(0)P(0)P(0) is true. The statement is of the form \mathbf{False}\implies pFalse  ⟹  p\mathbf{False}\implies pFalse⟹p which is always true. Such a proof is called a vacuous proof.

Remember that an integer nnnn is...

  • ...even if (and only if) n=2kn=2kn=2kn=2k for some integer kkkk.
  • ...odd if (and only if) n=2k+1n=2k+1n=2k+1n=2k+1 for some integer kkkk.

One way to prove that such a series of statements are equivalent is to prove the following implications:

  • (i) \implies  ⟹  \implies⟹ (ii)
  • (ii) \implies  ⟹  \implies⟹ (iii)
  • (iii) \implies  ⟹  \implies⟹ (iv)
  • (iv) \implies  ⟹  \implies⟹ (i)

(Why does this imply that all statements (i) to (iv) are equivalent?)

Another way is to prove the following equivalences:

  • (i) \iff  ⟺  \iff⟺ (ii)
  • (ii) \iff  ⟺  \iff⟺ (iii)
  • (iii) \iff  ⟺  \iff⟺ (iv)

Let nnnn be an integer. Then the following statements are equivalent:
i. nnnn is even.
ii. n+1n+1n+1n+1 is odd.
iii. 3n+13n+13n+13n+1 is odd.
iv. 3n3n3n3n is even.

Proof:
(i)\implies  ⟹  \implies⟹(ii): Since nnnn is even, we can write n=2kn=2kn=2kn=2k for some integer kkkk. Then n+1=2k+1n+1=2k+1n+1=2k+1n+1=2k+1 which is odd.
(ii)\implies  ⟹  \implies⟹(iii): Since n+1n+1n+1n+1 is odd, we can write n+1=2k+1n+1=2k+1n+1=2k+1n+1=2k+1 so 3n+1=6k+1=2k'+13n+1=6k+1=2k′+13n+1=6k+1=2k'+13n+1=6k+1=2k′+1 with k'=3kk′=3kk'=3kk′=3k so 3n+13n+13n+13n+1 is odd.
(iii)\implies  ⟹  \implies⟹(iv): Since 3n+13n+13n+13n+1 is odd, we can write 3n+1=2k+13n+1=2k+13n+1=2k+13n+1=2k+1 so 3n=2k3n=2k3n=2k3n=2k which is even.
(iv)\implies  ⟹  \implies⟹(i): Since 3n3n3n3n is even, we can write 3n=2k3n=2k3n=2k3n=2k so n=2k'n=2k′n=2k'n=2k′ with k'=k/3k′=k/3k'=k/3k′=k/3.

Here is how to proceed:

Here is an example showing how to prove the rule of implication elimination by using the resolution rule:

\begin{align*}
Res(p,F,q) &= ((p\vee F)\wedge(\neg p\vee q))\implies(F\vee q)\\
&\equiv (p\wedge(\neg p\vee q))\implies q\\
&\equiv (p\wedge(p\implies q))\implies q
\end{align*}
Res(p,F,q)=((p∨F)∧(¬p∨q))  ⟹  (F∨q)≡(p∧(¬p∨q))  ⟹  q≡(p∧(p  ⟹  q))  ⟹  q\begin{align*} Res(p,F,q) &= ((p\vee F)\wedge(\neg p\vee q))\implies(F\vee q)\\ &\equiv (p\wedge(\neg p\vee q))\implies q\\ &\equiv (p\wedge(p\implies q))\implies q \end{align*} Res(p,F,q)​=((p∨F)∧(¬p∨q))⟹(F∨q)≡(p∧(¬p∨q))⟹q≡(p∧(p⟹q))⟹q​
